title: The Amazing Interlude
creator: Mary Roberts Rinehart
description: LibriVox recording of The Amazing Interlude, by Mary Roberts Rinehart. Read by Mary Ann Spiegel. It is the early days of The Great War. As the curtain rises, Sara Lee is sitting by the fire in her aunt and uncle’s home, knitting a baby afghan. Her beau’s name is Harvey. He has his eye on a little house that is just perfect for two and he will soon propose to Sara Lee. But in this play, the mise en scène is about to change. A fairyland transformation will take place and Sara Lee will step into a new and different story, where she is the princess in a forest of adventure. There is a prince, too, whose name is Henri. He is as strange as the forest itself. And then just as suddenly, the scene changes back and Sara Lee is once again sitting alone by the fire, knitting socks for the soldiers this time, and with a memory and a new stirring in her heart. This is the story of Sara Lee’s amazing interlude. (Summary by MaryAnn) For further information, including links to online text, reader information, RSS feeds, CD cover or other formats (if available), please go to the LibriVox catalog page for this recording. For more free audio books or to become a volunteer reader, visit LibriVox.org. M4B format available
subject: librivox; literature; audiobook; war; fantasy; love; rinehart
source: Librivox recording of a public-domain text

reviews.reviewbody:
A story of courage and honor, with great characters and attention to detail.  The author was the first woman war correspondent at the Belgian front, so writes with sympathy and direct experience.

Note that the archive.org / Librivox.org description isn't literal; there's no fairlyland or actual prince. The story is both grounded -- and souring.

The narration is simply outstanding.

The Amazing Interlude is a story of personal sacrifice, honor, and romance at the Belgian front during World War I.  A wonderful story by Mary Roberts Rinehart, read beautifully by Librivox volunteer, MaryAnn.  MaryAnn has a lovely reading voice, measured and quiet--such a pleasure to listen to.  I look forward to more stories from both the writer and the reader.

I saw the summary and the author and got a mental picture in my head of the story.  However, when I started listening I realized it was a war story, not a mystery or a fantasy story.  It was a HUGE letdown for me.  

The heroine is supposed to be getting married soon, but the war is raging and she feels like she has to do something.  So, she attaches herself to a soldier and goes to the front to cook food for people.  This is the story of her encounters during the war.  

The reader was excellent.  5 stars for the reader, 1 for the story.
